cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 175 miles SW of Ft. Myers, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: moving north-northeast parallel to the west coast of Florida, then forecast to turn northeast, cross northern Florida, and exit into the western Atlantic toward the coasts of Georgia/South Carolina
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: west-central Florida coast (near Cedar Key/Yankeetown area)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Hurricane Watch from Anna Maria Island to Yankeetown, FL (west coast of Florida)
weather_observation.warning_coast: Tropical Storm Warning from Dry Tortugas and Bonita Beach to Suwannee River, FL
weather_observation.impacted_coast: West coast of Florida from Bonita Beach northward to Steinhatchee River (including Tampa Bay) with later impacts spreading across northern Florida and the southeast Georgia coastline
weather_observation.wind: Up to a 1-in-4 chance (25%) of sustained 39+ mph winds with occasional stronger gusts Friday as Eta’s remnant core passes just south of the Georgia coast.
weather_observation.storm_surge: None expected along the Georgia coast; surge threat confined to Florida’s Gulf coast.
weather_observation.rainfall: Periods of heavy rain Thursday night–Friday could total 1–3 inches, locally higher but generally below 4 inches near Brunswick.
weather_observation.other_hazards: High surf and dangerous rip currents possible along the Georgia beaches Friday–Saturday.
